<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->
<solution>
<ul>
  <li><p>Substitute the given points into the general equation to yield a system of two equations in two unknowns
    <md>
      <mrow>$m \amp= a b^{$p}</mrow>
      <mrow>$p2y \amp= a b^{$p2x}</mrow>
    </md>
  </p>
  </li>
  <li><p>Take the logarithm of both sides of each equation, then use properties of logarithms and rearrange to isolate a term in common to both equations, <m>\log(a)</m>.</p>
    <p>First equation:
    <md>
      <mrow>\log\bigg(\frac{$m}{a} \bigg) \amp= \log(b^{$p})</mrow>
      <mrow>\log($m) - \log(a) \amp= $p\log(b)</mrow>
      <mrow>\log($m) - $p\log(b) \amp= \log(a)</mrow>
    </md></p>
    <p>Second equation:
    <md>
      <mrow>\log\bigg(\frac{$p2y}{a}\bigg) \amp= \log(b^{$p2x})</mrow>
      <mrow>\log($p2y) - \log(a) \amp= ($p2x)\log(b)</mrow>
      <mrow>\log($p2y) - ($p2x)\log(b) \amp= \log(a)</mrow>
    </md></p>
  </li>
  <li><p>Each of these equations have a right-hand side equal to <m>\log(a)</m>. We can therefore set the left-hand sides equal to each other, simplify, and isolate the <m>\log(b)</m> term as follows
    <md>
      <mrow>\log($m) - $p \log(b) \amp= \log($p2y) - $p2x \log(b)</mrow>
      <mrow>$p2x \log(b) - $p \log(b) \amp= \log($p2y) - \log($m)</mrow>
      <mrow>\log(b^{$q}) \amp= \log($n)</mrow>
    </md>
  </p>
  </li>
  <li><p>Solve for <m>b</m>
    <md>
      <mrow>$q\log(b) \amp= \log($n)</mrow>
      <mrow>\log(b) \amp= \frac{\log($n)}{$q}</mrow>
      <mrow>10^{\log(b)} \amp= 10^{\frac{\log($n)}{$q}}</mrow>
      <mrow>b \amp\approx $bN</mrow>
    </md></p></li>
  <li><p>Solve either of the original equations for <m>a</m> by substituting the value found for <m>b</m>, being sure to keep 5-7 decimal digits as stored in your calculator
    <md>
      <mrow>$m \amp= a b^{$p}</mrow>
      <mrow>a \amp\approx \frac{$m}{$bN^{$p}}</mrow>
      <mrow>a \amp\approx $aN</mrow>
    </md>
  </p></li>
  <li>The final exponential growth model is 
    <me>y = $aN{displayDecimals="3"} \cdot $bN{displayDecimals="3"}^x</me>
  </li>
</ul>
    
</solution>
</problem>

